04418nam a22006615i 9780292772229DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211975txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927722297 a10.7560/7071222doi  a(DE-B1597)586960  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHG3881b.E26 7aBUS0230002bisacsh04a332.4/51 aEckes, Alfred E., Alfred E., Jr., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Search for Solvency :bBretton Woods and the International Monetary System, 1941-1971 /cAlfred E., Jr. Eckes, Alfred E. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1975  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 The Quest for a Durable Global Monetary System -- t2 America's Global Monetary Design -- t3 America and Britain: Divergent Approaches to a Common Goal -- t4 Consultation and Consensus -- t5 Prelude to Bretton Woods -- t6 Bretton Woods -- t7 Selling the "Magnificent Blueprint" -- t8 The Protracted Transition -- t9 "Death of Bretton Woods" -- t10 Epilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiverted by the dramatic military and political events of July 1944, few Americans realized the significance of an international conference taking place at Bretton Woods, a mountain resort in New Hampshire, far from the battle zones. There United Nations experts were completing plans for a world monetary and financial system that they hoped would create a prosperous, efficient global economy and avert economic tensions that might lead to another world war. Until the dollar crisis of 1971, decisions made at Bretton Woods provided the institutions and rules for international finance. The conference ushered in an era of unprecedented expansion of world trade and prosperity. Based on extensive research in previously unavailable sources, A Search for Solvency relates intriguing and often complicated issues of economic analysis and diplomatic history. It offers a succinct and comprehensive survey of international monetary development from the collapse of the pre–World War I gold standard to the devaluation of the dollar in 1971. In effect, it explains the origins of late twentieth-century global inflation and currency problems. The author details how the ghost of the Great Depression, the failure of monetary reconstruction efforts after World War I, and the memory of the nineteenth-century gold standard guided efforts to construct the Bretton Woods system. This preoccupation with the past, as well as political constraints, produced a monetary system protected against past dangers—fluctuating currencies, controls, and deflation—but dangerously vulnerable to inflationary pressures. The weaknesses of Bretton Woods, a system geared to an era in which economic power was concentrated in the United States, became visible in the 1960s and painfully apparent by the mid-1970s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aForeign exchange. 0aInternational finance. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292772229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292772229/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK